Direct Preference Optimization:
Your Language Model is Secretly a Reward Model
Rafael Rafailov∗†
Archit Sharma∗†
Eric Mitchell∗†
Stefano Ermon†‡
Christopher D. Manning†
Chelsea Finn†
†Stanford University ‡CZ Biohub
{rafailov,architsh,eric.mitchell}@cs.stanford.edu
Abstract
While large-scale unsupervised language models (LMs) learn broad world knowl-
edge and some reasoning skills, achieving precise control of their behavior is
difficult due to the completely unsupervised nature of their training. Existing
methods for gaining such steerability collect human labels of the relative quality of
model generations and fine-tune the unsupervised LM to align with these prefer-
ences, often with reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF). However,
RLHF is a complex and often unstable procedure, first fitting a reward model that
reflects the human preferences, and then fine-tuning the large unsupervised LM
using reinforcement learning to maximize this estimated reward without drifting","ANSWER: To adjust the behavior of language models without altering their fundamental structures, strategies like Fine-Tuning LMs on a small, value-focused dataset and Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) are employed. These approaches help enhance the model's capacity to comply with specific values by estimating a reward system that reflects human preferences and optimizing the language model accordingly.","To adjust the behavior of language models without altering their fundamental structures, strategies like Fine-Tuning LMs on a small, value-focused dataset and Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) are employed. These approaches help enhance the model's capacity to comply with specific values by estimating a reward system that reflects human preferences and optimizing the language model accordingly."
