Modelling the scaling behavior.
Understanding the scaling behaviour of language models and
their transfer properties has been important in the development of recent large models (Hernandez
et al., 2021; Kaplan et al., 2020). Kaplan et al. (2020) ﬁrst showed a predictable relationship between
model size and loss over many orders of magnitude. The authors investigate the question of choosing
the optimal model size to train for a given compute budget. Similar to us, they address this question
by training various models. Our work diﬀers from Kaplan et al. (2020) in several important ways.
First, the authors use a ﬁxed number of training tokens and learning rate schedule for all models; this
prevents them from modelling the impact of these hyperparameters on the loss. In contrast, we ﬁnd","Answer:
In the context of natural language processing tasks, a Large Language Model (LLM) refers to a language model that is trained with self-supervised machine learning on an extensive corpus of text. Specifically, it is designed for language generation tasks and its capabilities underpin modern chatbot systems. Notably, the largest and most proficient LLMs are Generative Pre-Trained Transformers (GPTs), which exhibit core abilities related to syntactic, semantic, and ontological aspects of human languages embedded within the corpora used during training. However, while acquiring predictive power in these areas, such models may also carry forward inaccuracies and biases prevalent in their training data.

