or expensive the procedure might be. The infinite memory gives a Turing machine an edge to be mathematically limitless. However, infinite memory is not feasible in real modern computers and then we only consider Turing machine as a mathematical model of

Neural Turing Machines#

controls the operation heads to read from or write to the tape. However, the memory in NTM is finite, and thus it probably looks more like a “Neural von Neumann Machine”.

Fig 10. Neural Turing Machine Architecture.","The Neural Turing Machine (NTM) doesn't directly simulate the infinite memory characteristic of Turing machines because of practical limitations in real-world computer systems. Instead, NTM uses a finite memory that behaves similarly due to its architecture. In particular, the NTM combines a neural network with a finite memory system that functions as a tape, where the neural network controls the positioning of read/write heads on the tape through learning mechanisms. This allows the NTM to emulate certain aspects of Turing machines while operating within the constraints of available resources. Therefore, one could argue that the NTM exhibits characteristics reminiscent of a ""Neural Von Neumann Machine"" rather than a true Turing machine with infinite memory.","The Neural Turing Machine (NTM) doesn't directly simulate the infinite memory characteristic of Turing machines because of practical limitations in real-world computer systems. Instead, NTM uses a finite memory that behaves similarly due to its architecture. In particular, the NTM combines a neural network with a finite memory system that functions as a tape, where the neural network controls the positioning of read/write heads on the tape through learning mechanisms. This allows the NTM to emulate certain aspects of Turing machines while operating within the constraints of available resources. Therefore, one could argue that the NTM exhibits characteristics reminiscent of a ""Neural Von Neumann Machine"" rather than a true Turing machine with infinite memory."
