[7] Denny Britz, Anna Goldie, Thang Luong, and Quoc Le. “Massive exploration of neural machine translation architectures.” ACL 2017.
[8] Ashish Vaswani, et al. “Attention is all you need.” NIPS 2017.

Attention Mechanisms#
In Neural Turing Machine, how to generate the attention distribution $\mathbf{w}_t$ depends on the addressing mechanisms: NTM uses a mixture of content-based and location-based addressings.
Content-based addressing","The attention mechanism addresses the challenge of memorizing long source sentences in Neural Machine Translation (NMT), which was previously limited by the in-between distance of dependencies between source and target sequences. By creating shortcuts between the context vector and the entire source input through customizable shortcut connections, the attention mechanism enables models to process entire sequences of text at once, facilitating the training of larger and more sophisticated models. This is achieved through the use of an attention distribution ($\mathbf{w}_t$) generated based on both content-based and location-based addressings (as seen in Neural Turing Machines). The methodology involves allowing the model to focus on specific parts of the source sentence when generating the corresponding part of the target sentence, thereby improving translations significantly.","The attention mechanism addresses the challenge of memorizing long source sentences in Neural Machine Translation (NMT), which was previously limited by the in-between distance of dependencies between source and target sequences. By creating shortcuts between the context vector and the entire source input through customizable shortcut connections, the attention mechanism enables models to process entire sequences of text at once, facilitating the training of larger and more sophisticated models. This is achieved through the use of an attention distribution ($\mathbf{w}_t$) generated based on both content-based and location-based addressings (as seen in Neural Turing Machines). The methodology involves allowing the model to focus on specific parts of the source sentence when generating the corresponding part of the target sentence, thereby improving translations significantly."
