maintain the optimizer states for most parameters. Instead, we only optimize the injected,","Answer: Applying LoRA to Transformer models offers significant computational efficiency benefits during both training and deployment phases. During training, LoRA leverages adaptive optimizers, requiring less computation per iteration since only the rank decomposition matrices of the dense layers undergoing adaptation are optimized, rather than calculating gradients or maintaining the optimizer state for all parameters. This approach can lower GPU memory requirements by up to 3 times when utilizing adaptive optimizers. Additionally, due to the ability to share a pre-trained model across various tasks, the model parameters remain unchanged during task switching, significantly reducing the overhead associated with storing multiple models for distinct tasks and the time required for switching between these tasks upon deployment.","Applying LoRA to Transformer models offers significant computational efficiency benefits during both training and deployment phases. During training, LoRA leverages adaptive optimizers, requiring less computation per iteration since only the rank decomposition matrices of the dense layers undergoing adaptation are optimized, rather than calculating gradients or maintaining the optimizer state for all parameters. This approach can lower GPU memory requirements by up to 3 times when utilizing adaptive optimizers. Additionally, due to the ability to share a pre-trained model across various tasks, the model parameters remain unchanged during task switching, significantly reducing the overhead associated with storing multiple models for distinct tasks and the time required for switching between these tasks upon deployment."
