7.1
WHICH WEIGHT MATRICES IN TRANSFORMER SHOULD WE APPLY LORA TO?","ANSWER: Applying LoRA to Transformer models offers significant benefits in terms of computational efficiency during both training and deployment. By inserting trainable low-rank decomposition matrices into each layer of the Transformer architecture instead of modifying the pre-trained model weights directly, we can reduce the number of trainable parameters significantly while maintaining similar performance. This approach, known as Low-Rank Adaptation (or LoRA), enables us to create multiple customized models tailored for different tasks without introducing additional latency compared to a finetuned model during inference. This is achieved through efficient switching between tasks by simply updating the LoRA weights rather than re-training the entire model. Furthermore, LoRA allows for the sharing and use of a single pre-trained model across various tasks, making it an effective method for deploying Transformer models","Applying LoRA to Transformer models offers significant benefits in terms of computational efficiency during both training and deployment. By inserting trainable low-rank decomposition matrices into each layer of the Transformer architecture instead of modifying the pre-trained model weights directly, we can reduce the number of trainable parameters significantly while maintaining similar performance. This approach, known as Low-Rank Adaptation (or LoRA), enables us to create multiple customized models tailored for different tasks without introducing additional latency compared to a finetuned model during inference. This is achieved through efficient switching between tasks by simply updating the LoRA weights rather than re-training the entire model. Furthermore, LoRA allows for the sharing and use of a single pre-trained model across various tasks, making it an effective method for deploying Transformer models"
