While pre-training a large language model has a considerable compute cost, downstream ﬁne-
tuning and inference also make up substantial compute usage (Rae et al., 2021). Due to being 4×
smaller than Gopher, both the memory footprint and inference cost of Chinchilla are also smaller.
4.1. Model and training details","Answer:
The efficiency of Chinchilla in terms of computing power for inference and fine-tuning can be attributed to its reduced model size compared to models like Gopher. This reduction in model size leads to a smaller memory footprint during both training and inference phases. Furthermore, due to having fewer parameters, Chinchilla requires less computational resources during the inference process. These factors collectively contribute to Chinchilla being more computationally efficient than larger models such as Gopher. However, it should be noted that while Chinchilla trains faster and consumes less compute during inference and fine-tuning stages, it was initially trained on 4x more data than Gopher, which might have affected its initial performance.","The efficiency of Chinchilla in terms of computing power for inference and fine-tuning can be attributed to its reduced model size compared to models like Gopher. This reduction in model size leads to a smaller memory footprint during both training and inference phases. Furthermore, due to having fewer parameters, Chinchilla requires less computational resources during the inference process. These factors collectively contribute to Chinchilla being more computationally efficient than larger models such as Gopher. However, it should be noted that while Chinchilla trains faster and consumes less compute during inference and fine-tuning stages, it was initially trained on 4x more data than Gopher, which might have affected its initial performance."
