Neural Turing Machines#

Fig 10. Neural Turing Machine Architecture.

Reading and Writing#
When reading from the memory at time t, an attention vector of size $N$, $\mathbf{w}_t$ controls how much attention to assign to different memory locations (matrix rows). The read vector $\mathbf{r}_t$ is a sum weighted by attention intensity:

$$
\mathbf{r}_t = \sum_{i=1}^N w_t(i)\mathbf{M}_t(i)\text{, where }\sum_{i=1}^N w_t(i)=1, \forall i: 0 \leq w_t(i) \leq 1
$$

NTM contains two major components, a controller neural network and a memory bank.
Controller: is in charge of executing operations on the memory. It can be any type of neural network, feed-forward or recurrent.
Memory: stores processed information. It is a matrix of size $N \times M$, containing N vector rows and each has $M$ dimensions.

Alan Turing in 1936 proposed a minimalistic model of computation. It is composed of a infinitely long tape and a head to interact with the tape. The tape has countless cells on it, each filled with a symbol: 0, 1 or blank ("" “). The operation head can read symbols, edit symbols and move left/right on the tape. Theoretically a Turing machine can simulate any computer algorithm, irrespective of how complex or expensive the procedure might be. The infinite memory gives a Turing machine an edge to be

where $w_t(i)$ is the $i$-th element in $\mathbf{w}_t$ and $\mathbf{M}_t(i)$ is the $i$-th row vector in the memory.
When writing into the memory at time t, as inspired by the input and forget gates in LSTM, a write head first wipes off some old content according to an erase vector $\mathbf{e}_t$ and then adds new information by an add vector $\mathbf{a}_t$.","Answer: The Neural Turing Machine (NTM) simulates the infinite memory characteristic of Turing machines through its attention mechanism during reading and writing processes. During reading, an attention vector controls the distribution of focus across various memory locations, effectively allowing the system to access relevant portions of the memory while ignoring less important ones. This emulation of focusing on specific areas within an infinite space replicates the concept of infinite memory without requiring actual infinite capacity. During writing, the erase and add vectors are used to modify existing data in the memory bank, thereby enabling the system to update and store new information, again mirroring the ability to manipulate arbitrary amounts of data that infinite memory provides.","The Neural Turing Machine (NTM) simulates the infinite memory characteristic of Turing machines through its attention mechanism during reading and writing processes. During reading, an attention vector controls the distribution of focus across various memory locations, effectively allowing the system to access relevant portions of the memory while ignoring less important ones. This emulation of focusing on specific areas within an infinite space replicates the concept of infinite memory without requiring actual infinite capacity. During writing, the erase and add vectors are used to modify existing data in the memory bank, thereby enabling the system to update and store new information, again mirroring the ability to manipulate arbitrary amounts of data that infinite memory provides."
multi-qa-mpnet-base-dot-v1,medium_context,1000,200,7,mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.3,research,0,What defines a large language model in the context of natural language processing tasks?,"A large language model (LLM) is a language model trained with self-supervised machine learning on a vast amount of text, designed for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation. The largest and most capable LLMs are generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and provide the core capabilities of modern chatbots. LLMs can be fine-tuned for specific tasks or guided by prompt engineering. These models acquire predictive power regarding syntax, semantics, and ontologies inherent in human language corpora, but they also inherit inaccuracies and biases present in the data they are trained on.

A large language model (LLM) is a language model trained with self-supervised machine learning on a vast amount of text, designed for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation. The largest and most capable LLMs are generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) and provide the core capabilities of modern chatbots. LLMs can be fine-tuned for specific tasks or guided by prompt engineering. These models acquire predictive power regarding syntax, semantics, and ontologies inherent in human language corpora, but they also inherit inaccuracies and biases present in the data they are trained on.

